UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# React Fundamentals — The Mental Model\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nReact is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces. It was created by Facebook in 2013 and is now used by virtually every major technology company. React''s core idea is simple: UI is a function of state.\n\n```\nUI = f(state)\n\nWhen state changes → React re-runs the function → UI updates\n```\n\nThis model makes UIs predictable, testable, and composable in ways that direct DOM manipulation cannot match.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Understand the core mental model of React (components, props, state)\n- Set up a React project with Vite\n- Understand the Virtual DOM and reconciliation\n- Know when React re-renders and why\n- Write your first React component\n\n---\n\n## 3. Core Mental Model\n\n```\nReact Application\n      │\n      ▼\n  Component Tree\n   App (root)\n   ├── Header\n   │   ├── Logo\n   │   └── Nav\n   │       ├── NavLink (Home)\n   │       ├── NavLink (Courses)\n   │       └── NavLink (Profile)\n   ├── Main\n   │   ├── CourseGrid\n   │   │   ├── CourseCard (HTML5)\n   │   │   ├── CourseCard (CSS3)\n   │   │   └── CourseCard (JavaScript)\n   └── Footer\n\nData Flow:\n  Parent → Children via Props\n  Children → Parent via Callbacks\n  Siblings → via Lifted State or Context\n\nRe-render triggers:\n  1. setState called with different value\n  2. Parent re-renders (new props passed)\n  3. Context value changes\n  4. useReducer dispatch called\n```\n\n## 4. Setup with Vite\n\n```bash\n# Create React + TypeScript project\nnpm create vite@latest my-app -- --template react-ts\ncd my-app\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n\n# Project structure\nmy-app/\n├── src/\n│   ├── main.tsx          # Entry point (renders <App>)\n│   ├── App.tsx           # Root component\n│   ├── components/       # Reusable components\n│   ├── pages/            # Page-level components\n│   ├── hooks/            # Custom hooks\n│   ├── lib/              # Utilities and services\n│   └── types/            # TypeScript interfaces\n├── index.html\n├── tsconfig.json\n└── vite.config.ts\n```\n\n## 5. Virtual DOM & Reconciliation\n\n```\nHow React updates the DOM:\n\n1. State changes: count = 5 → 6\n\n2. React calls your component function again\n   Returns new Virtual DOM (plain JS objects):\n   { type: "p", props: { children: "Count: 6" } }\n\n3. React compares (diffs) new vDOM vs previous vDOM\n\n4. React calculates the MINIMAL changes needed:\n   Only update the text node "Count: 5" → "Count: 6"\n\n5. React applies ONLY those changes to the real DOM\n   Result: One DOM text update instead of recreating everything\n\nThis is why React is efficient:\n- Real DOM operations are expensive (layout, paint)\n- Virtual DOM is just JavaScript object manipulation (cheap)\n- Minimal real DOM updates happen\n```\n\n## 6. Your First React Component\n\n```tsx\nimport { useState } from "react";\n\n// Functional component\nfunction App() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n  return (\n    <div className="app">\n      <h1>R-Learn</h1>\n      <p>Count: {count}</p>\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>\n        Increment\n      </button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\nexport default App;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the Virtual DOM and how does it improve performance?**\n> The Virtual DOM is an in-memory JavaScript representation of the real DOM. When state changes, React creates a new virtual DOM tree, diffs it against the previous one (reconciliation), and applies only the minimal necessary changes to the real DOM. This batches and minimizes expensive real DOM operations.\n\n**Q: What is reconciliation?**\n> Reconciliation is React''s algorithm for comparing the old and new virtual DOM trees to determine what changed. React uses a heuristic O(n) algorithm: elements of different types produce different trees; elements with stable keys are matched across renders. This determines the minimal set of real DOM updates needed.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `UI = f(state)` mean in React?\n2. What is the Virtual DOM?\n3. What are the three things that trigger a React re-render?\n4. What is reconciliation?\n5. What is the entry point file in a React Vite project?\n6. What are the main folders in a well-organized React project?\n7. How does data flow between components?\n8. What is the difference between a library and a framework?\n9. Why is React efficient despite re-running component functions on every state change?\n10. What version of React introduced Hooks?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| React | Library for building UI from components |\n| Component | Function that returns JSX |\n| Virtual DOM | JS representation of real DOM |\n| Reconciliation | Diffing old vs new vDOM |\n| Re-render | Component function runs again |\n| Data flow | Props down, callbacks up |\n\nReact''s mental model — UI as a function of state, managed via components — is elegant and powerful. Once it clicks, building complex UIs becomes a matter of composing small, focused components.', 20, 1)
WHERE id = 'l50101';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# JSX & Rendering — React''s Syntax Deep Dive\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nJSX (JavaScript XML) is the syntax extension that lets you write HTML-like code inside JavaScript. It looks like HTML but compiles to `React.createElement()` calls. Understanding JSX deeply — its rules, expressions, conditional rendering, and lists — is fundamental to React development.\n\n---\n\n## 2. JSX Rules & Syntax\n\n```tsx\n// JSX compiles to:\n<h1 className="title">Hello</h1>\n// React.createElement("h1", { className: "title" }, "Hello")\n\n// Rules:\n// 1. Must return a single root element\nreturn (\n  <div>  {/* Single root */}\n    <h1>Title</h1>\n    <p>Content</p>\n  </div>\n);\n\n// 2. Fragment — avoid extra div\nreturn (\n  <>  {/* Fragment shorthand */}\n    <h1>Title</h1>\n    <p>Content</p>\n  </>\n);\n\n// 3. class → className\n<div className="card active"> // NOT class=\n\n// 4. for → htmlFor on labels\n<label htmlFor="email">Email</label>  // NOT for=\n\n// 5. All tags must be closed\n<input type="text" />  // Self-closing\n<img src="..." alt="..." />  // Self-closing\n\n// 6. camelCase event handlers\n<button onClick={fn}>  // NOT onclick=\n<input onChange={fn}>\n<form onSubmit={fn}>\n\n// 7. JavaScript expressions in {}\n<p>{user.name}</p>\n<p>{2 + 2}</p>\n<p>{isAdmin ? "Admin" : "User"}</p>\n<p>{formatDate(user.createdAt)}</p>\n```\n\n## 3. Conditional Rendering\n\n```tsx\nfunction CourseCard({ course, isEnrolled, isAdmin }: Props) {\n  // Pattern 1: if/else return\n  if (!course) return <p>Course not found</p>;\n  if (loading)  return <div className="skeleton" />;\n\n  // Pattern 2: Ternary — for either/or\n  return (\n    <div className="card">\n      <h3>{course.title}</h3>\n\n      {/* Ternary: either/or */}\n      {isEnrolled\n        ? <button>Continue Learning</button>\n        : <button>Enroll Now</button>\n      }\n\n      {/* Short-circuit &&: show only if truthy */}\n      {isAdmin && (\n        <div className="admin-controls">\n          <button>Edit</button>\n          <button>Delete</button>\n        </div>\n      )}\n\n      {/* Nullish coalescing: default value */}\n      <p>{course.description ?? "No description available"}</p>\n\n      {/* !! Avoid: 0 && <Component> renders "0" */}\n      {/* WRONG */ count && <span>{count} items</span>}\n      {/* CORRECT */ count > 0 && <span>{count} items</span>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Lists & Keys\n\n```tsx\nfunction CourseGrid({ courses }: { courses: Course[] }) {\n  return (\n    <div className="grid">\n      {/* Map array to JSX elements */}\n      {courses.map(course => (\n        // KEY is required — must be stable and unique\n        <CourseCard\n          key={course.id}    // Use database ID — NEVER array index\n          course={course}\n        />\n      ))}\n\n      {/* Empty state */}\n      {courses.length === 0 && (\n        <div className="empty-state">\n          <p>No courses found</p>\n        </div>\n      )}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n// Why key matters:\n// Key = stable identifier for React to track elements across renders\n// With proper keys: React UPDATES existing elements\n// Without keys/wrong keys: React DESTROYS and RE-CREATES elements\n\n// WRONG keys:\ncourses.map((c, index) => <Card key={index} />)\n// If courses reorder or an item is removed, indexes shift\n// React gets confused — wrong elements update\n\n// CORRECT:\ncourses.map(c => <Card key={c.id} />)\n```\n\n## 5. Fragments and Portals\n\n```tsx\n// Fragment — return multiple elements without wrapper div\nfunction UserInfo({ user }) {\n  return (\n    <>\n      <dt>Name</dt>\n      <dd>{user.name}</dd>\n      <dt>Email</dt>\n      <dd>{user.email}</dd>\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\n// Fragment with key (for lists)\ncourses.map(course => (\n  <React.Fragment key={course.id}>\n    <dt>{course.title}</dt>\n    <dd>{course.level}</dd>\n  </React.Fragment>\n));\n\n// Portal — render outside the component tree (for modals)\nimport { createPortal } from "react-dom";\n\nfunction Modal({ children, isOpen }) {\n  if (!isOpen) return null;\n\n  return createPortal(\n    <div className="modal-overlay">\n      <div className="modal">{children}</div>\n    </div>,\n    document.getElementById("modal-root")! // Render outside React tree\n  );\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: Why does JSX use `className` instead of `class`?**\n> JSX compiles to JavaScript function calls. `class` is a reserved keyword in JavaScript. React uses `className` for the CSS class attribute to avoid the conflict. Similarly, `for` is a JavaScript loop keyword so labels use `htmlFor`.\n\n**Q: Why do list items need a `key` prop?**\n> Keys help React identify which items in a list changed, were added, or removed. During reconciliation, React uses keys to match elements across renders. Without stable keys, React might re-create elements unnecessarily (losing state and animations) or update the wrong elements. Always use stable, unique identifiers — never array indexes.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does JSX compile to?\n2. What is a React Fragment?\n3. Why must list items have a `key` prop?\n4. What is wrong with using array index as a key?\n5. What is the difference between `&&` and `||` in JSX?\n6. Why does JSX use `className` not `class`?\n7. How do you embed a JavaScript expression in JSX?\n8. What is a portal in React?\n9. Why can ''t you render `0` with `{count && <span>}` if count is 0?\n10. What is the self-closing rule in JSX?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| JSX Rule | Explanation |\n|---------|-------------|\n| Single root | Wrap in div or Fragment |\n| `className` | Not `class` |\n| `htmlFor` | Not `for` |\n| `{expression}` | JavaScript in JSX |\n| Self-close | `<img />` not `<img>` |\n| camelCase events | `onClick`, `onChange` |\n| Keys on lists | Stable, unique ID |\n| `&&` | Short-circuit: only shows if truthy |\n| Ternary | `? :` for either/or |\n\nJSX is React''s template syntax. Once you understand its rules and patterns, you can express any UI structure clearly and efficiently.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l50201';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Components & Props — Building Reusable UI Pieces\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nComponents are the fundamental building blocks of React. A component is a function that accepts props (inputs) and returns JSX (output). The entire art of React development is decomposing UI into the right components and composing them together.\n\nProps are how components communicate — data flows DOWN via props, events flow UP via callback props.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Component Design Principles\n\n```tsx\n// A good component:\n// 1. Does one thing well\n// 2. Accepts well-typed props\n// 3. Has sensible defaults\n// 4. Is reusable in different contexts\n// 5. Is easy to test\n\n// BAD: Component doing too much\nfunction CoursePageComponent({ id }: { id: string }) {\n  // Fetches data, handles auth, formats dates, renders, handles events...\n  // This is a "god component" — hard to test, can''t reuse parts\n}\n\n// GOOD: Decomposed components\n// CoursePageContainer — data fetching, auth\n// CourseHeader — title, level, author info\n// CourseModuleList — list of modules\n// EnrollButton — enrollment logic\n// CourseStats — enrolled count, rating, duration\n```\n\n## 3. Props Patterns\n\n```tsx\ninterface CourseCardProps {\n  // Required\n  id:          string;\n  title:       string;\n  level:       "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\n\n  // Optional with defaults\n  thumbnail?:   string;\n  description?: string;\n  enrolled?:    number;\n  rating?:      number;\n  isEnrolled?:  boolean;\n\n  // Callbacks\n  onEnroll?:   (id: string) => void;\n  onBookmark?: (id: string) => void;\n\n  // Render props / children\n  renderBadge?: () => React.ReactNode;\n  className?:   string;\n}\n\nconst DEFAULT_THUMBNAIL = "/images/default-course.jpg";\n\nfunction CourseCard({\n  id,\n  title,\n  level,\n  thumbnail = DEFAULT_THUMBNAIL,\n  description = "",\n  enrolled   = 0,\n  rating     = 0,\n  isEnrolled = false,\n  onEnroll,\n  onBookmark,\n  renderBadge,\n  className = "",\n}: CourseCardProps) {\n  const levelColors = {\n    Beginner:     "bg-green-100 text-green-800",\n    Intermediate: "bg-blue-100 text-blue-800",\n    Advanced:     "bg-purple-100 text-purple-800",\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <article className={`card ${className}`}>\n      <img src={thumbnail} alt={`${title} course thumbnail`} />\n\n      <div className="card-body">\n        {/* Custom badge via render prop */}\n        {renderBadge?.()}\n\n        <span className={`badge ${levelColors[level]}`}>{level}</span>\n        <h3 className="card-title">{title}</h3>\n        {description && <p className="card-description">{description}</p>}\n\n        <div className="card-stats">\n          {enrolled > 0 && <span>{enrolled.toLocaleString()} enrolled</span>}\n          {rating > 0 && <span>★ {rating.toFixed(1)}</span>}\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div className="card-actions">\n        {onBookmark && (\n          <button onClick={() => onBookmark(id)} aria-label="Bookmark course">\n            🔖\n          </button>\n        )}\n        {onEnroll && (\n          <button\n            onClick={() => onEnroll(id)}\n            disabled={isEnrolled}\n            className={isEnrolled ? "btn-ghost" : "btn-primary"}\n          >\n            {isEnrolled ? "Enrolled" : "Enroll Now"}\n          </button>\n        )}\n      </div>\n    </article>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Children & Composition\n\n```tsx\n// Container components — accept children\ninterface CardProps {\n  children:  React.ReactNode;\n  header?:   React.ReactNode;\n  footer?:   React.ReactNode;\n  className?: string;\n}\n\nfunction Card({ children, header, footer, className = "" }: CardProps) {\n  return (\n    <div className={`card ${className}`}>\n      {header && <div className="card-header">{header}</div>}\n      <div className="card-body">{children}</div>\n      {footer && <div className="card-footer">{footer}</div>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n// Usage — compose with different content\n<Card\n  header={<h2>HTML5 Fundamentals</h2>}\n  footer={<button>Enroll</button>}\n>\n  <p>Master the building blocks of the web.</p>\n  <Stats modules={12} lessons={40} />\n</Card>\n\n// Slot pattern — named slots\nfunction DashboardLayout({\n  sidebar,\n  header,\n  children,\n}: {\n  sidebar:  React.ReactNode;\n  header:   React.ReactNode;\n  children: React.ReactNode;\n}) {\n  return (\n    <div className="dashboard">\n      <header>{header}</header>\n      <aside>{sidebar}</aside>\n      <main>{children}</main>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## 5. Component Composition Patterns\n\n```tsx\n// 1. Compound Components (Context-based)\nconst TabsContext = React.createContext<{ active: string; setActive: (id: string) => void }>(\n  { active: "", setActive: () => {} }\n);\n\nfunction Tabs({ defaultTab, children }: { defaultTab: string; children: React.ReactNode }) {\n  const [active, setActive] = useState(defaultTab);\n  return (\n    <TabsContext.Provider value={{ active, setActive }}>\n      {children}\n    </TabsContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction TabList({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {\n  return <div role="tablist">{children}</div>;\n}\n\nfunction Tab({ id, label }: { id: string; label: string }) {\n  const { active, setActive } = useContext(TabsContext);\n  return (\n    <button\n      role="tab"\n      aria-selected={active === id}\n      onClick={() => setActive(id)}\n    >{label}</button>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction TabPanel({ id, children }: { id: string; children: React.ReactNode }) {\n  const { active } = useContext(TabsContext);\n  if (active !== id) return null;\n  return <div role="tabpanel">{children}</div>;\n}\n\nTabs.List  = TabList;\nTabs.Tab   = Tab;\nTabs.Panel = TabPanel;\n\n// Usage\n<Tabs defaultTab="html">\n  <Tabs.List>\n    <Tabs.Tab id="html" label="HTML" />\n    <Tabs.Tab id="css"  label="CSS" />\n  </Tabs.List>\n  <Tabs.Panel id="html"><p>HTML content...</p></Tabs.Panel>\n  <Tabs.Panel id="css"><p>CSS content...</p></Tabs.Panel>\n</Tabs>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between props and state?**\n> Props are external inputs to a component, passed from a parent. They are read-only within the component — you cannot modify props. State is internal data owned by the component. State can change over time, triggering re-renders. Props flow down the tree; state stays local (unless lifted).\n\n**Q: What is prop drilling and how do you solve it?**\n> Prop drilling is passing props through many intermediate components that don''t use them, just to get data to a deeply nested component. Solutions: (1) Context API for global state, (2) Component composition (render props, children), (3) State management library (Zustand, Redux), (4) Restructuring the component tree.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are props in React?\n2. Can a component modify its own props?\n3. What is the children prop?\n4. What is a compound component pattern?\n5. What is prop drilling?\n6. What are the principles of good component design?\n7. What is a render prop?\n8. How do you pass a callback to a child component?\n9. What is the difference between controlled and uncontrolled components?\n10. When should you split a component into smaller components?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| Props | Read-only inputs from parent |\n| Children | Content between JSX tags |\n| Defaults | `prop = defaultValue` in destructuring |\n| Callbacks | Function props for child→parent communication |\n| Composition | Build complex UI from simple components |\n| Compound | Tightly-coupled components sharing context |\n\nComponent composition is the core skill of React development. Think in components — small, focused, reusable pieces that compose into complex UIs. The best React code is a tree of simple, well-named components.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l50301';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# useEffect & Lifecycle — Side Effects in React\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\n`useEffect` is for side effects — operations that interact with the outside world: data fetching, subscriptions, timers, DOM mutations, logging. React''s rendering is supposed to be a pure function of state. Everything that breaks that purity belongs in useEffect.\n\nUnderstanding useEffect deeply — especially the dependency array and cleanup — is where most React performance bugs and stale closure issues originate.\n\n---\n\n## 2. useEffect Fundamentals\n\n```tsx\nimport { useEffect, useState } from "react";\n\nfunction UserProfile({ userId }: { userId: string }) {\n  const [user, setUser]       = useState<User | null>(null);\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n  const [error, setError]     = useState<string | null>(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    // This runs AFTER render, when userId changes\n    let cancelled = false;  // Cleanup flag\n\n    async function fetchUser() {\n      setLoading(true);\n      setError(null);\n      try {\n        const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);\n        if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);\n        const data: User = await res.json();\n        if (!cancelled) setUser(data);   // Only update if still mounted\n      } catch (err) {\n        if (!cancelled) setError((err as Error).message);\n      } finally {\n        if (!cancelled) setLoading(false);\n      }\n    }\n\n    fetchUser();\n\n    // Cleanup: runs when userId changes or component unmounts\n    return () => {\n      cancelled = true;\n    };\n  }, [userId]); // Dependency array: re-run when userId changes\n\n  if (loading) return <div>Loading...</div>;\n  if (error)   return <div>Error: {error}</div>;\n  if (!user)   return null;\n  return <div>{user.name}</div>;\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Dependency Array Rules\n\n```tsx\n// 1. Empty array [] — run once on mount\nuseEffect(() => {\n  initializeAnalytics();\n  return () => cleanup();\n}, []);\n\n// 2. Values in array — run when any value changes\nuseEffect(() => {\n  fetchCourses(category, level);\n}, [category, level]); // Re-run when category OR level changes\n\n// 3. No array — run after EVERY render (usually wrong!)\nuseEffect(() => {\n  document.title = `${count} items`;\n}); // Runs every render — usually use [count] instead\n\n// Dependency array rules (ESLint enforces these):\n// Include EVERY reactive value used inside the effect\n// Reactive values: state, props, variables/functions defined in component\n// NOT reactive: stable values, ref.current, setState functions\n```\n\n## 4. Cleanup Functions\n\n```tsx\n// Cleanup is CRITICAL for:\n// 1. Subscriptions (WebSocket, EventSource)\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const ws = new WebSocket("wss://api.rlearn.com/live");\n  ws.onmessage = (e) => setMessages(prev => [...prev, JSON.parse(e.data)]);\n  ws.onerror   = (e) => console.error(e);\n  return () => ws.close();  // Close when component unmounts\n}, []);\n\n// 2. Event listeners\nuseEffect(() => {\n  function handleKeyDown(e: KeyboardEvent) {\n    if (e.key === "Escape") setModalOpen(false);\n  }\n  document.addEventListener("keydown", handleKeyDown);\n  return () => document.removeEventListener("keydown", handleKeyDown);\n}, []); // Only attach once\n\n// 3. Timers\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const timer = setInterval(() => setTime(new Date()), 1000);\n  return () => clearInterval(timer); // Prevent memory leak\n}, []);\n\n// 4. AbortController for fetch\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const controller = new AbortController();\n\n  async function fetchData() {\n    try {\n      const res = await fetch("/api/data", { signal: controller.signal });\n      const data = await res.json();\n      setData(data);\n    } catch (err) {\n      if ((err as Error).name !== "AbortError") setError(err);\n    }\n  }\n\n  fetchData();\n  return () => controller.abort(); // Cancel in-flight request\n}, []);\n```\n\n## 5. Common useEffect Patterns\n\n```tsx\n// Pattern 1: Sync state to localStorage\nuseEffect(() => {\n  localStorage.setItem("theme", theme);\n}, [theme]); // Runs when theme changes\n\n// Pattern 2: Update document title\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const original = document.title;\n  document.title = `${pageTitle} — R-Learn`;\n  return () => { document.title = original; };\n}, [pageTitle]);\n\n// Pattern 3: Intersection Observer for lazy loading\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(\n    entries => entries.forEach(e => { if (e.isIntersecting) loadMore(); }),\n    { threshold: 0.5 }\n  );\n  if (sentinelRef.current) observer.observe(sentinelRef.current);\n  return () => observer.disconnect();\n}, [loadMore]);\n\n// Pattern 4: Debounce user input for search\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const timer = setTimeout(() => {\n    if (searchQuery.trim()) fetchSearchResults(searchQuery);\n  }, 300);\n  return () => clearTimeout(timer); // Cancel if query changes before 300ms\n}, [searchQuery]);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between useEffect with [], no array, and [dependency]?**\n> No array: runs after every render. Empty array []: runs once after mount. [dep]: runs after mount and every time dep changes. Most effects need dependencies — the ESLint exhaustive-deps rule helps you include all reactive values.\n\n**Q: Why do you need cleanup in useEffect?**\n> Cleanup prevents memory leaks and stale updates. Without cleanup: (1) Event listeners stack up on every re-render. (2) Subscriptions keep firing after component unmounts. (3) Fetch callbacks try to update state on unmounted components (warning: "Can''t perform state update on unmounted component"). The cleanup function runs when the effect''s deps change or the component unmounts.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. When does useEffect run relative to rendering?\n2. What does an empty dependency array `[]` mean?\n3. When is the cleanup function called?\n4. What is a stale closure in useEffect?\n5. How do you cancel a fetch request in useEffect?\n6. Why should you include all dependencies in the array?\n7. What problem does the `cancelled` flag solve?\n8. When would you NOT use useEffect for data fetching?\n9. What is the exhaustive-deps ESLint rule?\n10. How is useLayoutEffect different from useEffect?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Pattern | When |\n|---------|------|\n| `[]` | Once on mount |\n| `[dep]` | On mount + when dep changes |\n| Cleanup | Subscriptions, listeners, timers, fetch |\n| Cancelled flag | Prevent state updates after unmount |\n| AbortController | Cancel in-flight fetch requests |\n\nuseEffect is the escape hatch from React''s pure rendering model. Use it for effects, not computations. Every effect that creates a resource (subscription, timer, fetch) needs a cleanup that releases it.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l50601';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# React Router — Navigation & Routing\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nReact Router is the standard routing library for React applications. It enables navigation between "pages" in a Single Page Application (SPA) — without full page reloads. The URL changes, the component tree updates, but the browser never makes a full navigation request.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Setup & Basic Routing\n\n```bash\nnpm install react-router-dom\n```\n\n```tsx\n// src/main.tsx\nimport { BrowserRouter } from "react-router-dom";\nimport App from "./App";\n\nReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root")!).render(\n  <BrowserRouter>\n    <App />\n  </BrowserRouter>\n);\n\n// src/App.tsx\nimport { Routes, Route, Navigate } from "react-router-dom";\nimport { Layout } from "./components/Layout";\nimport { HomePage } from "./pages/HomePage";\nimport { CoursesPage } from "./pages/CoursesPage";\nimport { CourseDetailPage } from "./pages/CourseDetailPage";\nimport { LessonPage } from "./pages/LessonPage";\nimport { ProfilePage } from "./pages/ProfilePage";\nimport { SignInPage } from "./pages/auth/SignInPage";\nimport { NotFoundPage } from "./pages/NotFoundPage";\n\nfunction App() {\n  const { isAuthenticated } = useAuth();\n\n  return (\n    <Routes>\n      {/* Public routes */}\n      <Route path="/signin" element={<SignInPage />} />\n\n      {/* Protected routes */}\n      <Route element={<ProtectedRoute />}>\n        <Route element={<Layout />}>\n          <Route index element={<HomePage />} />\n          <Route path="courses" element={<CoursesPage />} />\n          <Route path="courses/:courseId" element={<CourseDetailPage />} />\n          <Route path="courses/:courseId/lessons/:lessonId" element={<LessonPage />} />\n          <Route path="profile" element={<ProfilePage />} />\n          <Route path="profile/:userId" element={<ProfilePage />} />\n        </Route>\n      </Route>\n\n      {/* Redirects */}\n      <Route path="/home" element={<Navigate to="/" replace />} />\n\n      {/* 404 */}\n      <Route path="*" element={<NotFoundPage />} />\n    </Routes>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Hooks & Navigation\n\n```tsx\nimport {\n  useParams,\n  useNavigate,\n  useLocation,\n  useSearchParams,\n  Link,\n  NavLink,\n  Outlet,\n} from "react-router-dom";\n\n// useParams — access URL parameters\nfunction CourseDetailPage() {\n  const { courseId } = useParams<{ courseId: string }>();\n  // URL: /courses/html5-fundamentals → courseId = "html5-fundamentals"\n}\n\n// useNavigate — programmatic navigation\nfunction LoginForm() {\n  const navigate = useNavigate();\n\n  async function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent) {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    await login(formData);\n    navigate("/dashboard");           // Go to dashboard\n    navigate(-1);                     // Go back\n    navigate("/", { replace: true }); // Replace history entry\n    navigate("/courses", { state: { from: "enrollment" } }); // Pass state\n  }\n}\n\n// useLocation — access current location\nfunction Breadcrumb() {\n  const location = useLocation();\n  // location.pathname = "/courses/html5/lessons/intro"\n  // location.search   = "?tab=content"\n  // location.hash     = "#summary"\n  // location.state    = { from: "enrollment" }\n}\n\n// useSearchParams — URL query parameters\nfunction CoursesPage() {\n  const [searchParams, setSearchParams] = useSearchParams();\n  const category = searchParams.get("category") ?? "all";\n  const page     = Number(searchParams.get("page") ?? "1");\n\n  function handleCategoryChange(cat: string) {\n    setSearchParams({ category: cat, page: "1" });\n    // Updates URL: /courses?category=frontend&page=1\n  }\n}\n\n// Link — navigation without page reload\n<Link to="/courses">Browse Courses</Link>\n<Link to={`/courses/${course.id}`}>View Course</Link>\n\n// NavLink — Link with active state\n<NavLink\n  to="/courses"\n  className={({ isActive }) => isActive ? "nav-link active" : "nav-link"}\n>\n  Courses\n</NavLink>\n\n// Outlet — renders child route\nfunction Layout() {\n  return (\n    <div className="layout">\n      <Navbar />\n      <main><Outlet /></main>\n      <Footer />\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Protected Routes\n\n```tsx\nimport { Navigate, Outlet, useLocation } from "react-router-dom";\n\nfunction ProtectedRoute() {\n  const { isAuthenticated, isLoading } = useAuth();\n  const location = useLocation();\n\n  if (isLoading) return <div>Loading...</div>;\n\n  if (!isAuthenticated) {\n    // Redirect to signin, remember where they were going\n    return <Navigate to="/signin" state={{ from: location }} replace />;\n  }\n\n  return <Outlet />; // Render the child route\n}\n\n// After login, redirect back to original destination\nfunction SignInPage() {\n  const navigate  = useNavigate();\n  const location  = useLocation();\n  const from      = (location.state as { from?: Location })?.from?.pathname ?? "/";\n\n  async function handleLogin(data: LoginFormData) {\n    await login(data);\n    navigate(from, { replace: true }); // Go back to where they were\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between BrowserRouter and HashRouter?**\n> BrowserRouter uses the HTML5 History API — URLs look like `/courses/html5`. Requires server config to serve index.html for all paths. HashRouter uses `#` — URLs look like `/#/courses/html5`. Works with static file servers (GitHub Pages) because the server only sees `/`, never the hash part. Use BrowserRouter for all modern applications.\n\n**Q: What is the purpose of `replace` in `navigate("/path", { replace: true })`?**\n> `replace: true` replaces the current history entry instead of adding a new one. This means the back button won''t go back to the previous page. Use it for redirects (after login, after form submission) — you don''t want users pressing Back and going to the login page again.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `<Outlet />` render?\n2. How do you access URL parameters?\n3. What is the difference between `Link` and `<a>`?\n4. How do you protect a route?\n5. What does `useNavigate` return?\n6. How do you pass state during navigation?\n7. What are query parameters and how do you access them?\n8. What is the difference between `BrowserRouter` and `HashRouter`?\n9. What does `replace: true` do in navigation?\n10. How does nested routing work?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Hook/Component | Purpose |\n|---------------|--------|\n| `<Routes>` | Route container |\n| `<Route>` | Define a route |\n| `<Link>` | Client-side navigation |\n| `<NavLink>` | Link with active state |\n| `<Outlet>` | Render child routes |\n| `useParams` | Access URL params |\n| `useNavigate` | Programmatic navigation |\n| `useLocation` | Current URL info |\n| `useSearchParams` | Query string params |\n\nReact Router is the navigation layer of React apps. Nested routes, protected routes, and URL-driven state make applications bookmarkable, shareable, and feel like real web experiences.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l50701';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Context API — Sharing State Without Prop Drilling\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nContext provides a way to share values between components without explicitly passing them through every level of the tree. It solves prop drilling — the pattern where you pass props through many intermediate components just to get data to a deeply nested child.\n\nCommon uses: authentication state, theme, locale/language, shopping cart, user preferences.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Creating & Using Context\n\n```tsx\nimport { createContext, useContext, useState, useCallback, useMemo } from "react";\n\n// 1. Define the shape\ninterface AuthContextValue {\n  user:          User | null;\n  isLoading:     boolean;\n  isAuthenticated: boolean;\n  signIn:        (email: string, password: string) => Promise<void>;\n  signOut:       () => Promise<void>;\n}\n\n// 2. Create with default (null + type assertion pattern)\nconst AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextValue | null>(null);\n\n// 3. Build the Provider component\nexport function AuthProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {\n  const [user, setUser]       = useState<User | null>(null);\n  const [isLoading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n\n  const isAuthenticated = user !== null;\n\n  // Load user on mount\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const unsubscribe = supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange((event, session) => {\n      setUser(session?.user ? formatUser(session.user) : null);\n      setLoading(false);\n    });\n    return unsubscribe;\n  }, []);\n\n  // Stable callbacks — won''t cause unnecessary re-renders\n  const signIn = useCallback(async (email: string, password: string) => {\n    const { error } = await supabase.auth.signInWithPassword({ email, password });\n    if (error) throw error;\n  }, []);\n\n  const signOut = useCallback(async () => {\n    await supabase.auth.signOut();\n    setUser(null);\n  }, []);\n\n  // Memoize value to prevent unnecessary re-renders\n  const value = useMemo((): AuthContextValue => ({\n    user,\n    isLoading,\n    isAuthenticated,\n    signIn,\n    signOut,\n  }), [user, isLoading, isAuthenticated, signIn, signOut]);\n\n  return (\n    <AuthContext.Provider value={value}>\n      {children}\n    </AuthContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\n// 4. Custom hook — typed and safe\nexport function useAuth(): AuthContextValue {\n  const context = useContext(AuthContext);\n  if (!context) {\n    throw new Error("useAuth must be used within an AuthProvider");\n  }\n  return context;\n}\n\n// 5. Usage in any component\nfunction Navbar() {\n  const { user, isAuthenticated, signOut } = useAuth();\n\n  return (\n    <nav>\n      {isAuthenticated ? (\n        <>\n          <span>Hello, {user?.name}</span>\n          <button onClick={signOut}>Sign Out</button>\n        </>\n      ) : (\n        <Link to="/signin">Sign In</Link>\n      )}\n    </nav>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Multiple Contexts\n\n```tsx\n// Each context has single responsibility\nconst ThemeContext  = createContext<ThemeContextValue | null>(null);\nconst CartContext   = createContext<CartContextValue | null>(null);\nconst ToastContext  = createContext<ToastContextValue | null>(null);\n\n// Provider composition\nfunction AppProviders({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {\n  return (\n    <AuthProvider>\n      <ThemeProvider>\n        <ToastProvider>\n          <CartProvider>\n            {children}\n          </CartProvider>\n        </ToastProvider>\n      </ThemeProvider>\n    </AuthProvider>\n  );\n}\n\n// In main.tsx\n<AppProviders>\n  <App />\n</AppProviders>\n```\n\n## 4. Context Performance Optimization\n\n```tsx\n// Problem: Context re-renders ALL consumers on ANY value change\n// Solution: Split frequently-changing state\n\n// BAD: One context with everything\ninterface AppContext {\n  user:           User;   // Rarely changes\n  notifications:  number; // Changes often\n  onlineStatus:   boolean; // Changes often\n}\n// Every notification update re-renders ALL components using AppContext!\n\n// GOOD: Split by update frequency\nconst UserContext   = createContext<User | null>(null);\nconst NotifContext  = createContext<number>(0);\nconst StatusContext = createContext<boolean>(true);\n\n// Components only re-render when THEIR context changes\nfunction ProfileButton() {\n  const user = useContext(UserContext);\n  // Only re-renders when user changes — not on notifications!\n}\n\nfunction NotificationBell() {\n  const count = useContext(NotifContext);\n  // Only re-renders when notification count changes\n}\n\n// Also: memoize context value with useMemo\nconst value = useMemo(\n  () => ({ user, signIn, signOut }),\n  [user, signIn, signOut] // Only re-create when these change\n);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: When should you use Context vs prop drilling vs state management?**\n> Prop drilling (1-2 levels): fine, no overhead. Context: for global state accessed across many components (auth, theme, locale). State management (Zustand, Redux): for complex state with many actions, when you need DevTools time-travel debugging, or when performance is critical. Context is not a replacement for state management — it''s a dependency injection mechanism.\n\n**Q: Why should you memoize the Context value?**\n> The Context Provider re-renders when its parent re-renders. Without memoization, a new object is created each render — all consumers re-render even if the data didn''t change. With `useMemo`, the value object is only recreated when its dependencies change, preventing unnecessary consumer re-renders.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is prop drilling and how does Context solve it?\n2. What does `createContext` take as an argument?\n3. Why do you create a custom hook for context?\n4. What causes all context consumers to re-render?\n5. How do you memoize a context value?\n6. What happens if you use a context hook outside its Provider?\n7. When should you use Context vs Zustand/Redux?\n8. What is the Provider pattern?\n9. Can you nest contexts of the same type?\n10. What is the "context splitting" performance pattern?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Step | Code |\n|------|------|\n| Create context | `createContext<Type>(null)` |\n| Provider | `<Context.Provider value={...}>` |\n| Consume | `useContext(Context)` |\n| Custom hook | `function useX() { const ctx = useContext(X); if (!ctx) throw Error; return ctx; }` |\n| Performance | `useMemo` for value, split contexts by frequency |\n\nContext is React''s built-in dependency injection. Use it for values that need to be accessible across many components (auth, theme, locale). For performance, split your context and memoize values.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l50801';
